### reasoning 
1. Perception Layer (Object Understanding)
The system first converts raw grids into structured symbolic objects.
Process:
Connected component detection (BFS flood-fill)
Object extraction from pixel space
Feature encoding: size, color, centroid, bounding box
Output:
Structured object list
Scene representation
2. Abstraction Layer (Concept Formation)
Transforms raw objects into higher-level concepts.
Capabilities:
Shape normalization
Spatial encoding (relative positioning)
Pattern compression into task signature
Detected concepts:
SIZE_CHANGE
COLOR_TRANSFORM
SYMMETRY
SPATIAL_TRANSLATION
 3. Rule Inference Engine
Generates candidate transformation rules from examples.
Rule Types:
MOVE(dr, dc)
ROTATE(90/180/270)
RECOLOR(a → b)
SCALE(factor)
FLIP(H / V)
Mechanism:
compares input vs output object geometry
detects delta transformations
votes across multiple examples
 4. Symbolic Program Synthesis
Builds executable programs from inferred rules.
Program structures:
Sequential rules
Conditional execution
Loop-based transformations
Example:
Plain text
[("MOVE", 1, 0), ("RECOLOR", 2, 3)]
 5. Search & Optimization Engine
Explores possible programs using beam search.
Features:
heuristic scoring
partial match evaluation
pruning low-probability branches
depth-limited exploration
Goal: Find program P such that:

P(input) ≈ output
6. Memory & Analogy System
Stores past successful solutions for reuse.
Functions:
Task signature encoding
Program recall via similarity matching
Analogical transfer learning
Benefit: Speeds up solving similar unseen tasks.
 7. Reflection & Validation Layer
Validates correctness of generated programs.
Checks:
Output equality
Structural match
Shape consistency
Failure classification
Errors detected:
SHAPE_ERROR
CONTENT_ERROR 

Input Grid
   ↓
Object Engine
   ↓
Abstraction Layer
   ↓
Rule Inference
   ↓
Program Synthesis
   ↓
Search Optimization
   ↓
Validation
   ↓
Final Output Grid

### more

Adaptation System (Fast Learning Engine)
The adaptation module allows HPMI to adjust its strategy based on task difficulty and failure patterns.
Functions:
Detects repeated failure types
Adjusts search depth dynamically
Changes beam width based on uncertainty
Switches rule priorities automatically
Behavior:
Easy task → fast shallow reasoning
Hard task → deep symbolic search
Repeated error → strategy shift
🔷 2. Intuition Layer (Heuristic Guessing Engine)
Simulates “intuition” using compressed pattern recognition from past experience.
Functions:
Similarity-based shortcut reasoning
Pattern compression memory
Rapid candidate rule suggestion
Effect:
Reduces search space
Improves first-guess accuracy
Enables near-instant partial solutions
🔷 3. Thinking Engine (Multi-Path Reasoning Core)
Generates multiple competing hypotheses instead of a single logic path.
Mechanism:
Parallel rule generation
Competing program candidates
Ranking via scoring function
Modes:
Logical reasoning path
Spatial reasoning path
Symbolic transformation path
🔷 4. Memory System (Long-Term Knowledge Store)
Stores structured experience from solved tasks.
Components:
Task signatures
Successful programs
Failure patterns
Rule confidence scores
Capabilities:
Retrieval of similar tasks
Reuse of known solutions
Confidence-based rule selection
🔷 5. Meta-Control System (Self-Regulation Layer)
Controls how all other modules behave.
Responsibilities:
Chooses reasoning depth
Enables/disables modules dynamically
Balances speed vs accuracy
Detects overfitting behavior
🔷 6. Abstraction Compression Layer
Reduces raw grid complexity into minimal symbolic representation.
Functions:
Object merging
Pattern simplification
Structural encoding
Feature reduction
🔷 7. Failure Analysis System
Learns from incorrect outputs.
Detects:
Missing rule types
Wrong transformation assumptions
Search failures
Overgeneralization
Output:
Repair suggestions
New operator creation hints
🔷 8. Operator Evolution System
Creates new transformation rules when existing ones fail.
Examples:
ALIGN_OBJECTS
MIRROR_SHIFT
OBJECT_SPLIT
PATTERN_DUPLICATION
🔷 9. Confidence Scoring System
Assigns reliability score to every rule and program.
Based on:
Past success rate
Task similarity
Execution stability
🔷 10. Hybrid Reasoning Core
Combines all systems into one unified pipeline:
Plain text
Perception → Abstraction → Intuition → Rule Inference → Search → Memory → Reflection → Output

### final summary 
HPMI is a multi-layer symbolic reasoning system designed to solve ARC-style grid transformation tasks using:
Object-based perception
Rule inference from examples
Symbolic program synthesis
Beam search optimization
Memory-based analogical recall
Self-reflection and error correction
The system does not rely on direct pattern matching. Instead, it constructs executable transformation programs that generalize across unseen tasks.
